<p>These tokens are created on Cardano&#8217;s native token standard, allowing developers to issue their own digital assets and build unique functionalities within their decentralized applications. The role of native tokens can be best understood through a visual representation:</p>



<figure class="wp-block-table"><table><thead><tr><th>Role of Native Tokens in Cardano&#8217;s DApps</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><strong>1. Utility Tokens</strong></td><td>Native tokens can be used as utility tokens within the DApps, providing access to certain features or services.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>2. Governance Tokens</strong></td><td>Native tokens can be utilized as governance tokens, enabling holders to participate in decision-making processes within the DApps ecosystem.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>3. Asset Tokens</strong></td><td>Native tokens can represent real-world assets such as property, stocks, or commodities, allowing for seamless tokenization and transfer of ownership.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>4. Fundraising Tokens</strong></td><td>Native tokens can serve as fundraising tokens, facilitating Initial Coin Offerings (ICOs) or token sales to raise funds for project development.</td></tr></tbody></table></figure>



<p>Through the diverse roles of native tokens, Cardano&#8217;s DApps ecosystem fosters innovation, decentralization, and economic empowerment.</p>



